State Seeks Return of Yadkin River Flows, Hydroelectric License to the†People of North Carolina

Gov. Bev Perdue†this week announced that the State of North Carolina has filed papers with the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) seeking return of the right to plan the use of the Yadkin River flows and the Yadkin hydroelectric project for the benefit of the people of North Carolina.

‚ÄúFifty years ago, we endorsed Alcoa‚Äôs request for a federal license to operate hydroelectric dams because the project created jobs for up to 1,000 North Carolinians,‚Äù said Perdue.† ‚ÄúToday, those jobs are gone, and so is the reason for the license.‚Äù

‚ÄúThe State of North Carolina is responsible for the health and well-being of its citizens,‚Äù Perdue said. ‚ÄúGiven the Yadkin River‚Äôs broad impact on the state, we believe strongly that the state is the most appropriate body to plan use of this invaluable natural resource, to help assure the region‚Äôs municipal water supply and quality and to facilitate future growth and development.‚Äù

The Yadkin River Basin includes nearly a quarter of the state‚Äôs 100 counties, representing 17.5 percent of its population.

The initial federal license for the Yadkin hydroelectric facilities, which expired in 2008, was granted more than 50 years ago to Alcoa Power Generating Inc. APGI developed a series of dam and hydroelectric plants to serve the industrial needs of its parent company, Alcoa Inc., namely, its aluminum smelting plant in nearby Badin, which required a significant amount of power. The facilities comprising the Yadkin Project have essentially determined how the Yadkin River flows have been used in the state for the past 100 years.

